post_text:
We are seeking input from our community to ensure that our plans are designed to best serve our students and keep everyone safe and healthy. We invite you to join us on Monday, July 27th from 6-7 to build on our Reopening Framework and inform the plan for fall. We believe it is critical to have input from teachers, administrators, parents, and students to ensure the best possible plan. We look forward to your input.

Our goals for the meeting include:

Provide a high-level overview of “Reopening Framework”

Align our learning model based on what worked and what didn’t

Provide feedback on draft models for remote and hybrid schedules for the fall

Zoom Link: https://zoom.us/j/92533776836

post_text:
Goldendale School District is requesting input from families on Fall 2020 reopening options.

We are required to adhere to Department of Health and Labor and Industries requirements set forward by the Office of Public Instruction (OSPI). These include:

1) Wearing masks
2) Physical distancing
3) Screening for COVID symptoms upon entering our buildings
4) Hand washing protocols
5) Cohorts - smaller groups of students K-8 staying together
6) Cleaning procedures

Our preference is to have all students at school on a regular schedule. However, we would not be able to meet the guidelines above. We are exploring other options that will allow us to keep our students and staff healthy while providing the best possible learning environment.

If you have students in GSD please share you input by completing this survey https://forms.gle/ehG97KQavEAVMmuu5

We are focused on the quality of education as well as logistics defined by COVID. We care about our students, families, and community.

post_text: Angie Hedges will be the Goldendale Primary School Principal starting next school year. Angie has the knowledge and skills to lead GPS into their next phase of growth. Angie's expertise in pedagogy and professional learning, her knowledge of the community and GPS, and her precision of leadership make her an excellent fit. While GHS will feel the loss of Angie's leadership, this is the best move for our students.

post_text:
Good morning

The CoVID19 situation is creating an ever changing landscape. In light of guidance and in communication with other districts and ESD105 we are postponing all activities, including athletic events and field trips out of our immediate region until after April 12. More information is anticipated either later this afternoon or early next week.

In addition, here are links to the CDC guidance for schools
https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/community/schools-childcare/guidance-for-schools.html.
and WA Department of Health
https://www.doh.wa.gov/Portals/1/Documents/1600/coronavirus/1-RecommendationsChildCareandSchools.pdf

Thank you for your patience and understanding as we navigate this ever changing situation.

Ellen Perconti, Superintendent

post_text:
To make a long story short, Klickitat County was offering an EMT-B class in Husum and all the Fire Agencies on the East side of the county had 15 prospective students that wanted to attend, but due to the distance to get to class decided not to attend. We started talking to the course instructors and the State of Washington about how we could accommodate those students to take the class. We came up with the first ever distance learning solution for EMS Training. Never before in the State have they done this type of class and they are looking closely at the results. In this class we hold at Goldendale High School 3 days a week, we have volunteer Firefighters from Alderdale, Goldendale, Roosevelt, Rural 7 and Wishram. This class finishes at the end of May and soon these departments will have much needed EMT's to serve their communities. Thank you to Goldendale School District in assisting us in making this happen!
Robert Huwe, Captain Goldendale Fire Department

post_text:
Parents and Community Members,
As you may know, our school district no longer has an early release on Wednesdays for the remainder of this current school year. I mentioned in an earlier notice that our schools might need to change the length of our parent-teacher conferences to recover student class time that was lost due to the snow days.
After working together with our staff, it became very apparent that teachers not lose their important quality conference time with families in order to share how their children are doing in class. Therefore, the conference schedule will remain the same as planned on March 28-31st.
Also, the Goldendale School District will extend the school year by one additional day to Friday, June 16th. The students will be dismissed at noon that day.
Thank you for your understanding and we look forward to seeing you at the parent conferences.

Mr. Heid

post_text: Mr. Heid, we were at the ESD At Show this weekend. The forwarded e mail was a result of 4 out of 5 entries by Goldendale winning an award. I will talk with the kids to see if they would like to present to the board. Thanks again, Scott

post_text: I just wanted to share a few photos with you from the last couple of days. I had the great pleasure of talking twelve Goldendale students to The Dalles to participate in the annual Mid-Columbia Honor Band. Seven participated the Junior Band (7th-9th) grade and five participated in the Senior Band (10th-12th) grade. Over the course of two days, they participated in 12 hours of rehearsals with students from all around the Gorge to prepare and preform a concert as the grand finale. I'm incredibly impressed by the hard work they put in and the grit they demonstrated. They represented themselves, their families, our schools, and our community very well and I am proud to be their teacher! Mr. Danny Schneider

post_text:
Morning everyone, it is great to be back in school today. We are working closely with our regional ESD and state OSPI to figure out exactly how we make up all of the snow days missed. We are looking in to what changes if any may need to take place for our graduation date. It looks like we will need to add additional minutes to our weekly calendar to make sure we meet the required minutes for student contact time. It looks like we will be adding additional days as well. When we get the final word on how this process needs to be put in we will be working with our local associations to make sure it is done correctly. When we know what needs to be done we will share that with everyone. Have a great day!

"You can't cross the sea merely by staring at the water." - Rabindranath Tagore

Living the Dream, Mark

Mark Heid, Superintendent

post_text: We just got off the phone with state officials and Gov. Inslee has waived a number of snow days. What this means for us is that we will have school on the 3 snow days that we have on our calendar. We will not need to go to school Friday, June 16 and Monday, June 19. Graduation will be on the same day and school will be ending the same day as the current school calendar, If more weather hits that cause us to miss additional days then those dates will change.

Morning everyone, I would like to thank all of our maintenance crew for working such long hours to clean up all of the snow and ice around the district so that when weather has allowed, it has been safe to be on school grounds. They have also taken care of some inside issues to make sure that the buildings are warm. Thanks guys! Also a big shout out to our transportation people who have prepared the buses and braved the elements and safely got our kids home.

This is School Board Appreciation Month and I would like to thank our board members for all of their work and support behind the scenes that no one ever sees.

"If I do not practice one day, I know it. If I do not practice the next day, the orchestra knows it. If I do not practice the third day, the whole world knows it." - Ignace Paderewski, Polish Pianist

post_text:
Morning everyone, it was only 2 degrees this morning driving it so please be careful when you need to be outside and keep a close eye on the kids today. Thanks, I was given by a staff member a list entitled- 10 things that require zero talent- I believe that it fits in nicely with our growth mindset training. Doing these things regardless of any talents staff or students bring to the table will greatly increase success for all. I thought I would share it with all of you today.

10 THINGS THAT REQUIRE ZERO TALENT

BEING ON TIME
WORK ETHIC
EFFORT
BODY LANGUAGE
ENERGY
ATTITUDE
PASSION
BEING COACHABLE
DOING EXTRA
BEING PREPARED

These are 10 great things we can model for kids everyday!

"Grit... is intensity. Grit is the ability to enjoy responding to intimidation and adversity." - Norm Evans

Living the Dream, Mark

Mark Heid, Superintendent

Goldendale School District No. 404 Core Covenants:
Integrity - (Who we are; What we stand for)
Respect - (Effort and Attitude)
Commitment - (Empowering Everyone Through Education)

"If you keep doing the things the same way you have always done them, you will keep getting whatever you have gotten." - Unknown
